        "excerpt": "Then they gave money to the masons and carpenters, and food, drink and oil to the Sidonians and to the Tyrians, to bring cedar wood from Lebanon to the sea at Joppa, according to the permission they had from Cyrus king of Persia.",
        "body": "A single verse bridges the altar section and the foundation section, and it does so by invoking the Solomonic typology that runs through Ezra-Nehemiah. The procurement chain — Phoenician craftsmen, Lebanese cedar, the port of Joppa — is lifted almost verbatim from 1 Kings 5:6-11 and 2 Chronicles 2:15-16. Solomon and Hiram of Tyre; Zerubbabel and the Sidonians and Tyrians. The parallel is not incidental. The narrator is locating the second temple within the legitimate succession of Solomonic building.\n\nThe mention of 'the permission of Cyrus king of Persia' (3:7) grounds the project in the political reality of the Persian period while simultaneously subordinating that reality to a higher authorization. Cyrus has given permission, but the project is not Cyrus's. The authorization flows through him from YHWH who moved his spirit (1:1). The returnees work within the structures of imperial permission without being defined by them.\n\nThe payments — money to the masons and food, drink, and oil to the Phoenicians — reflect standard ancient Near Eastern labor contracts. The returnees are not operating in a spiritual vacuum but in a real economic and political world. The chapter's theology is not escapist; it is incarnate. The cedar must still travel by sea; the workers must still be paid. The God who is restoring Israel is doing so through ordinary commercial transactions in a Persian-authorized building project.\n\n> **Hebrew note.** *Rishyon* (permission, v.7) is an Aramaic loanword, reflecting the administrative vocabulary of the Persian empire. Its use here is historically authentic — Persian bureaucracy formalized building permits. The narrator's inclusion of this detail is not legalistic but realistic: covenant restoration happens in history, not above it."
